{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}
'''Dislocated worker funding''' is typically used to help workers in events of mass employment loss. In the [[United States of America | United States]] several grants have been established by the [[United_States_Secretary_of_Labor|Secretary of Labor]] known officially as National Dislocated Worker Grants. The grants provide resources for states or other applicants to mitigate job losses caused by large, unexpected layoffs.<ref name=doleta/> The grants were established in 2014 by the [[Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act]].

==Grants==

The grants have been used for a variety of reasons in the United States since their creation. A common reason is layoffs attributed to aging energy infrastructure such as end-of-life coal power plants or closing coal mines.<ref name=doleta>{{cite web |url=https://www.doleta.gov/DWGs/ |title=National Dislocated Worker Grants |work=U.S. Department of Labor |publisher=U.S. Department of Labor |accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=KULR8>{{cite web |url=http://www.kulr8.com/story/38205224/colstrip-awarded-nearly-1-million-grant-for-workforce-planning-and-worker-training/ |title=Colstrip awarded nearly $1 Million grant for workforce planning and worker training |work=kulr8.com |publisher=kulr8.com |accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref>

