[[File:Heavy Metal im Fantasy 16.jpg|thumb|Distinctive features: clothing, habit, and codes]]
In sociology, '''distinction''' is a social force that assigns different values upon different people in societies. In ''[[La Distinction|Distinction: A Social Critique of the Judgement of Taste]]'' (''La Distinction'', 1979), [[Pierre Bourdieu]] described how the [[power (sociology)|powers that be]] define [[aesthetics|aesthetic]] concepts such as "[[Taste (aesthetics)|taste]]", whereby the [[social class]] of a person tends to determine his or her cultural interests, likes, and dislikes, and how political and socio-economic, racial and sexual distinctions, based upon social class, are reinforced in daily life within society. Moreover, in ''[[The Rebel Sell|The Rebel Sell: Why the Culture Can't be Jammed]]'' (2004),  [[Joseph Heath]] and [[Andrew Potter]] describe "distinction" as a social competition in which the styles of social [[fashion]] are in continual development, and that the men and women who do not follow the development of social trends soon become stale, and irrelevant to their social-class stratum.

